<TEXT>
president daniel arap mois word has been 
political law for years in this oneparty state but it grows 
steadily more difficult for him to stem demands for political 
pluralism 
a loose alliance of churchmen lawyers and politicians ignored 
his latest order to stop campaigning for a multiparty democracy 
its leaders continued meeting with journalists and issuing press 
releases 
they have suffered telephoned threats open police surveillance 
and condemnation in parliament 
critics say the situation belies kenyas image as a stable 
democracy and describe the govermnent of moi and his kenya african 
national union party as increasingly corrupt and authoritarian 
it is a very serious situation said gibson kamau kuria a 
human rights lawyer and former political detainee the government 
is not respecting the laws of the country if the threat continues 
were witnessing the beginning of the end of a civil society as we 
know it in kenya 
kuria and 18 other lawyers signed a document calling for a legal 
opposition to keep the government on its toes and to keep it 
awake to the rights freedoms and aspirations of the people 
kenya has been at peace since independence from britain in 1963 
it often is cited as an example of stability and prosperity on a 
continent known more for guerrilla warfare military juntas and 
corrupt dictatorship 
it became a oneparty state in effect when its first president 
jomo kenyatta proscribed the only opposition party in 1969 it 
became one by law in 1982 with a constitutional amendment that 
banned opposition parties even though none existed 
demands for change began jan 1 in an address by the rev 
timothy njhoya long a critic of the government the presbyterian 
pastor urged africans to reflect on the experience of eastern 
europe and choose multiparty democracy 
in may two former cabinet ministers charles rubia and kenneth 
matiba took the message to a news conference they have been 
followed ever since by plainclothes security agents but continue 
demanding that the government allow a public meeting on the 
question 
my own view is there is overwhelming support for allowing a 
political opposition but i want to put it to the test matiba 
said in an interview moi has rejected what he terms foreign 
ideologies peddled by some unpatriotic people with borrowed 
brains and said those who tried to divide the nation would be 
hunted down like rats 
he claims the existence of about 40 tribes in kenya would invite 
tribalbased parties ethnic divisions and even tribal warfare 
critics say his rigidity signals political stagnation that could 
lead to mass unrest 
i see problems and i see trouble and my children have no 
future unless things change matiba said 
