<TEXT>
mikhail s gorbachev could lose his job as head of 
the communist party this week ousted by democratic reforms that 
have allowed hardliners to tighten their grip on the party 
gorbachev had intended to use this weeks 28th congress of the 
soviet communist party to try to further democratize the party 
accelerating reforms and ridding top party bodies of opponents 
he wants delegates to change party statutes and to endorse major 
changes in the top party bodies the 12member politburo and the 
249member central committee 
for the first time in history however the party leader has 
surrendered some control over the agenda and delegate selection 
conservatives say they plan to try to force gorbachev out of his 
job as party general secretary although he would retain the newly 
expanded post of soviet president 
gorbachev has sought to shift authority from the party to the 
government but loyalty to the party remains strong in the 
military the kgb security police and government bodies 
losing control of the party would jeopardize his reforms and 
career 
if the two posts were to be separated now in order to satisfy 
some peoples slogans the country could end up with anarchy and 
confrontation he has said 
whether or not conservatives actually follow through with the 
threats to dump gorbachev such open talk is unprecedented in 72 
years of soviet history 
no one can safely guess the outcome although one top western 
diplomat ventured friday that it looks incredibly likely that 
gorbachev will be reelected party leader 
no party leader has ever been ousted by a party congress and 
the public threats by hardliners in the past two weeks underscore 
the openness that gorbachev has introduced into the party 
there have been only three other parallels in soviet history 
and they are not exact said thane gustafson a professor at 
georgetown university 
the first was the 10th party congress in 1921 when vladimir 
lenin allied himself with bureaucrats to defeat the workers 
opposition the second was the 17th party congress in 1934 when 
the heavyhanded policies of josef stalin came under fire 
prompting him to launch a murderous purge of party ranks the 
following year 
and the third was the 20th party congress in 1956 when nikita 
s khrushchev was so uncertain of the reaction that he waited until 
the last day to deliver a secret speech condemning stalin 
hardliners failed in a conspiracy to oust him in 1957 but 
succeeded in 1964 
in the past the party leader controlled the agenda and could 
block any vote that may have directly threatened his job or 
policies 
but gorbachev may lose control of the agenda in the same way 
that he lost control last month of the founding congress of the 
communist party of the russian republic which provided hardliners 
with a national tribune 
this is quite an unprecedented setting gustafson said 
