<TEXT>
life appeared to return to normal today 
for the first time in a week following an aborted military coup and 
the deaths of 23 protesters in the countrys worst urban violence 
in history 
president kenneth kaunda played golf and long lines formed 
before dawn outside state stores private supermarkets and gasoline 
stations such services were closed after studentled rioting over 
higher food prices broke out one week ago 
no unrest was reported but the government kept a nighttime 
curfew in effect 
state television sunday night reported that more than 1000 
people had been arrested mainly for curfew violations during the 
violence but witnesses said many people were arrested in daylight 
during the antigovernment protests 
today paramilitary police and troops patrolled the streets of 
lusaka the capital and other cities and towns of this southern 
african country of 75 million 
officials said no one was killed during the coup attempt 
saturday but witnesses and diplomats said three civilians 
celebrating kaundas reported death were shot dead 
kaunda 67 was in the central city of ndola early saturday when 
a signal corps lieutenant announced on state radio that the army 
had seized power 
but loyalist troops detained the soldier and at least four other 
officers involved in the coup plot diplomats said on condition of 
anonymity the government has acknowledged the arrests of only two 
people 
the broadcasts prompted thousands of zambians to take to the 
streets to hail the reported coup and denounce kaunda 
in an apparent move to consolidate control kaunda on sunday 
transferred army commander ltgen gary kalenge former air force 
chief ltgen hanniah lungu was appointed defense minister a post 
that had been vacant 
kaunda gave no explanations for the moves 
the antigovernment protests began last monday and were led by 
students who denounced a stateordered price increase for corn 
meal the nations staple and demanded kaunda resign and 
multiparty democracy be restored at least 23 protesters were 
killed in clashes with security forces 
over the weekend the president vowed to crack down on enemies 
and refused to budge on the 120 percent price increase for cornmeal 
kaunda is under pressure from a faltering economy and foreign 
creditors who are owed 75 billion 
in similar rioting in december 1986 security forces shot to 
death at least 15 civilians kaunda rescinded the price increases 
at that time 
</TEXT>
