a man lost his murder appeal today in the 
clifffalling death of a woman he met married and insured just 
weeks after running a newspaper personal advertisement 
the maine supreme judicial court unanimously turned down each of 
the challenges raised by dennis r larson who is serving a 50year 
prison sentence in the death of kathy frost larson 
mrs larson plunged 80 feet to her death at otter cliffs in 
acadia national park on oct 11 1987 authorities centered their 
investigation on larson after learning he had collected insurance 
money when his first wife allegedly washed away in a montana stream 
larson 40 was convicted of murdering the former miss frost in 
a plot to collect 400000 in life insurance money but he 
challenged his appeal by saying the state improperly took 
statements from him 
the great falls mont man also said that during his trial 
superior court justice jack o smith improperly let the state 
reopen its case after the prosecutor failed to prove that the body 
found at the base of the cliff was that of his bride 
larson also challenged the use of testimony from an old friend 
who recounted a trip when larson said he would like to marry a 
foreign woman arrange an apparently accidental death then collect 
insurance money 
the states highest court found no merit in any of larsons 
arguments 
the state presented more than adequate evidence to warrant the 
superior courts belief beyond a reasonable doubt that defendant 
did indeed intentionally or knowingly murder kathy frost larson 
wrote chief justice vincent l mckusick 
the high court also said that maine was able to bring the murder 
charge against larson because the state and federal governments 
share jurisdiction in acadia 
larsons first wife leslee reynolds larson vanished in 1975 
with larson being the only witness larson claimed that the woman 
was washed away in prickly pear creek some 50 miles south of great 
falls 
no traces of leslee larson were ever found which authorities 
considered unusual under the circumstances and she was pronounced 
dead seven years later larson collected a 20000 payment from 
allstate insurance 
after larson was divorced from a second wife in montana he came 
to maine in june 1987 larson soon joined a computer dating service 
and ran several personal advertisements in area newspapers 
including the one that miss frost responded to 
within two weeks of their first meeting larson proposed 
marriage they married on sept 20 1987 
the next morning the newlyweds met with an insurance agent 
they purchased a policy that included 200000 coverage for mrs 
larson with a double indemnity for accidental death 
on oct 10 1987 the couple went to acadia national park the 
next day larson reported that his wife had fallen from the cliffs 
larson initially said his wife had wandered off alone looking 
for sea otters but friends and family did not believe it because 
the woman had been terrified of heights 
