<TEXT>
two cargo ships collided in the chesapeake 
bay during a thunderstorm severely damaging one of the ships and 
spilling at least 35000 gallons of fuel authorities said 
cleanup crews remained on station today after working through 
the night to contain the spill from this ships fuel tanks after 
the sunday evening collision some oil washed up on city beaches 
we consider this a major marine casualty because of the damage 
done and the amount of oil spilled said us coast guard cmdr 
george naccara 
naccara said 35000 gallons to 40000 gallons of no 4 heavy oil 
and diesel were spilled when the columbus america registered in 
west germany and the neptune jade based in singapore collided 
shortly before 7 pm sunday about five miles north of norfolk near 
the hampton roads bridgetunnel 
the 635foot columbus america received extensive damage and the 
neptune jade was also damaged naccara said but no injuries were 
reported on either ship 
capt eugene johnson commander of the coast guard marine safety 
office in portsmouth said the 6mile norfolk shipping channel 
remained closed this morning while efforts were made to corral the 
oil 
some oil washed ashore on beaches from willoughby spit to little 
creek in norfolk a distance of several miles johnson said cleanup 
would take several days and a lot of manual labor 
coast guard workers and a private contractor strung 
oilcontainment booms along the harbor protecting marinas and the 
waterside festival park a major shopping and tourist attraction 
the regions main resort area virginia beach on the atlantic 
ocean would probably be spared johnson said 
the columbus america was taken to the norshipco yard on the 
southern branch of the elizabeth river the ship had a hole below 
the water line and 12 of its cargo containers were severely 
damaged he said six containers went overboard but were recovered 
johnson said however that none of the cargo containers leaked 
both vessels were carrying hazardous material including petroleum 
distillates paint and lacquer products 
the columbus america held about 140000 gallons of fuel naccara 
said coast guard and navy personnel spent most of the night 
stringing containment booms around the ship and using oil skimmers 
to pick up as much of the spill as possible 
naccara said a coast guard helicopter was in the air at first 
light to survey the extent of the spill 
the accident happened as severe thunderstorms and high winds 
battered the area the national weather service had issued a marine 
warning and severe weather watches for the area before the crash 
the cause of the accident was under investigation according to 
coast guard spokesman rick woods both the coast guard and the 
national transportation safety board will take part in the 
investigation 
johnson said the crew had been given drug tests as a routine 
matter but the results will not be available for at least a couple 
of days 
 
