can the irish love the english are they 
wrapped in a celtic shell or part of the european whole and when 
is an irishman an irishman 
these are some of the intriguing issues that arise in the 
euphoria sweeping ireland over its teams performance at the world 
cup soccer tournament 
from the prime minister to the 300000 welcoming irish who 
filled the streets of dublin on sunday from the editorials in the 
press to the banter in a thousand pubs all irish eyes have been on 
team manager jack charlton and his lads 
as one huge banner across the airport highway put it banally 
but truthfully irish eyes are smiling 
that the teams accents are more english than irish matters 
little nor does the fact that to irish purists soccer is a 
foreign import that manager charlton is a purebred englishman 
does not prevent some pundits proposing he be made president of 
ireland 
and that ireland was knocked out in the quarterfinals does not 
stop the nation behaving as though it won the cup 
reaching the quarterfinals in irelands first appearance in the 
tournament has been reason enough to fill the streets with the 
largest crowds seen in dublin since pope john paul ii visited in 
1979 
people stood for six hours for a glimpse of their heroes waving 
everything from irish flags to inflatable rubber shamrocks they 
hung from trees lampposts and the statue of oliver goldsmith 
outside trinity college 
the two opentopped doubledecker buses bringing the team from 
the airport needed three hours to inch through the throng and 
though the irish came home beaten the multitudes were singing 
oh well really shake em up when we win the wororld cup 
yes ireland is the greatest football team 
the event cast interesting light on the myriad cultural and 
linguistic strands that bind ireland to england its ancient foe 
many of the irish players belong to english league teams and are 
descendants of irish emigrants a couple of them claim irish 
citizenship on the strength of a single grandparent 
the team commented the irish times is a mixture of 
fullirish partbritish and a variety of other races thrown in 
the manager is a fullblown geordie from the newcastle area of 
northern england 
but the captain mick mccarthy said of the crowd sunday in a 
broad north england accent theyve made us feel very very proud 
to be irish and despite what many people may say every member of 
this team is 110percent irish 
irish sport can make potent politics the gaelic athletic 
association long a vehicle of irish nationalism has always 
regarded soccer as an alien sport and still wont lend its stadiums 
to soccer matches 
but an association official pat daley acknowledged that a 
greater degree of ecumenism is inevitable 
in an interview he noted that the associations limerick 
chapter had proposed lending its ground to an irelandsoviet union 
soccer game 
permission wasnt forthcoming he said but the very notion 
would have been unheard of 10 years ago 
during the world cup games the association ran tv ads extolling 
its sports trying to show that the sports of hurling and gaelic 
football are more exciting than soccer but for as long as ireland 
was in the world cup no sport but soccer mattered 
it was the most liberating few weeks ive ever experienced in 
ireland wrote columnist nuala o faolain in the irish times 
her paper felt the team brought us closer to the wider world 
including our near neighbors they have brought about a great 
boosting of national morale which is not limited by class or creed 
or politics 
they have shown that there is a way to be proud of being 
irish without triumphalism or resentment toward those of other 
races and traditions they have done well for ireland 
ireland played tenacious defense in the opening matches to gain 
a 11 tie with england a scoreless tie with egypt and a 11 
deadlock with a strong dutch team in the second round ireland 
defeated romania on penalty kicks to advance to the quarterfinals 
where italy defeated the irish team 10 on saturday 
the bighearted irish gave most of their adulation not to 
homegrown heroes but to charlton the blunt 55yearold former 
soccer star who turned a nondescript team into one of the world 
cups top eight 
the aircraft bringing the team home was renamed st jack in his 
honor and the crowds chanted over and over we want jack 
as the irish press commented if as our history shows we 
have had a pretty raw deal from england over the past 800 years 
then she has made some amends by giving us jack charlton 
</TEXT>
