<TEXT>
teachers union leader albert shanker says the 
public is grasping at radical school reforms because the 
educational system is not taking the initiative and he blames 
footdragging administrators 
in an interview on the eve of the american federation of 
teachers annual convention the president of the 744000member 
union said administrators have responded to the national clamor for 
better schools with a lot of public relations and no action 
the country is 100 percent full of verbal commitment for 
change but thats where it ends verbal he said sunday 
as the convention got under way this morning he gave a 
stateoftheunion address telling the 3200 delegates that 
the groups membership has grown by 70000 in the past two years 
and outlining achievements during the groups 75year history 
shanker will deliver a second speech on wednesday dealing with 
educational issues he said in the interview it will likely include 
sharp criticism of school boards and superintendents who he says 
have failed to respond zealously to school reform 
shanker has said he also blames the bush administration for a 
very poor record of commitment on implementing the national 
education goals agreed upon in february by bush and the 50 
governors 
still shanker opened the convention by reading a brief message 
from first lady barbara bush congratulating the union on its 75th 
anniversary she said her work in literacy had taught her that 
teachers cannot do the job alone 
teachers reserved their warmest greeting for massachusetts gov 
michael dukakis who told cheering delegates we should be 
holding this convention in the east room of the white house there 
are some folks in washington who could use some education 
other scheduled speakers at the aft gathering this week include 
senator edward kennedy dmass and us secretary of education 
lauro cavazos 
in the interview shanker said a central theme of this years 
gathering will be his belief that radical school reorganization in 
chicago and the spreading popularity of choice plans that let 
parents decide where to send their children to school are among 
growing signs of public impatience with the pace of reform 
a resolution to be voted on by aft delegates later this week 
reiterates the unions openness to choice schemes but adds the 
unions opposition to any such plan that includes public funding of 
private schools 
shanker said his union has been open to such reform ideas as 
choice and merit pay but administrators have too rarely responded 
with leadership he said 
the convention runs through thursday the rival 2millionmember 
national education association will gather in kansas city on 
thursday through sunday 
later today the aft was to release findings of its annual 
teacher salary survey showing average us pay topping 31000 
other issues to be tackled this week by teacher delegates 
include a resolution calling for phasing out standardized 
multiplechoice testing a notion the aft considered dangerously 
radical less than a decade ago 
the convention will also play host to some 60 foreign delegates 
many of them from emerging democracies in eastern europe 
a resolution would commit the aft to helping budding democratic 
teacher unions in those countries 
jan urban a former czechoslovak teacher who was instrumental in 
helping elect czechoslavak president vaclav havel will address the 
convention later in the week 
