<TEXT>
the japanese government moving to improve 
trade relations with the united states agreed to toughen 
enforcement of antimonopoly laws on companies in japan the 
justice departments top antitrust official said monday 
the changes in laws against pricefixing bidrigging group 
boycotts and other practices should improve the ability of 
american companies to sell products in japan said james rill 
assistant attorney general for antitrust 
lax antitrust enforcement in japan has been a major sticking 
point in talks to reduce the huge us trade deficit with japan 
we are very very positive about these steps by the japanese 
for they represent in a oneyear period a very very substantial 
departure from the practices that existed before rill said of 
the agreement reached last week in tokyo 
the japanese government has promised to step up criminal 
enforcement of existing laws propose higher fines for civil 
antitrust violations and make private lawsuits easier to pursue in 
japans courts 
tougher antitrust enforcement is expected to reduce group 
boycotts of products which some have called a way of life in 
japan rill said 
the changes should erase the hurdle posed by those boycotts 
on us importation and other countries importation of products 
into japan he said 
japans free trade commission also agreed to make public its 
legal and factual findings in antitrust cases so that private 
plaintiffs can pursue lawsuits 
the two nations announced agreement last week on a wideranging 
package of economic reforms aimed at eliminating many trade 
barriers and reducing disputes over trade issues that have soured 
the usjapan relationship the united states currently runs about 
a 49 billion trade deficit with japan 
rill dismissed the notion that the japanese have a history of 
not keeping commitments on trade matters 
we dont believe they would make these public commitments 
after such arduous talks over such a long period of time without an 
intention to follow through on them he said 
the procurement and transport ministries have agreed to increase 
efforts to root out bidrigging and to increase the time that 
companies guilty of such collusion would be barred from getting 
government contracts he said 
