the chief of the tactical air command learned 
after the panama invasion that stealth fighterbombers missed their 
targets but did not tell his superiors because he believed others 
had done so a spokesman said today 
col ron sconyers a spokesman for gen robert d russ said in 
a telephone interview from tactical air command headquarters at 
langley air force base va that it was at least 10 to 15 days 
after the operation before russ learned of the missed targets 
sconyers said russ assumed that officers who were in the 
operational chain of command for the invasion as he was not would 
have informed their superiors at the pentagon and that it was not 
necessary for him to do so 
the spokesman said russ did take steps to improve training as a 
result of the information he had received 
the new york times reporting on what it said was a classified 
air force report said in todays editions that the lack of 
information led defense secretary dick cheney to brag about how 
accurate the bombing had been when bombs actually missed by as much 
as 160 yards 
the newspaper also said the report concluded there were defects 
in planning the panama operation confusion over the mission of the 
planes poor coordination between the army and the air force in 
picking targets and inadequate pilot training for the weather 
conditions over the targets 
russ gave the newspaper a statement saying he had left it up to 
army commanders to tell the pentagon how the invasion fared 
sconyers said neither he nor russ had seen the classified report 
general russ eventually knew that the aircraft had missed its 
targets but not early on sconyers said 
in the panama operation the spokesman said russ whose command 
controls the air force fighter planes is basically just a 
supplier of aircraft he is not part of the operational chain of 
command 
because he wasnt part of the operational chain of command and 
doesnt receive or generate operational reports he made the 
assumption that that would be done through the operational chain of 
command sconyers said 
in hindsight he would have done it a little differently the 
spokesman said 
there was never any intent on gen russ part at all to 
withhold information he said in fact he acted on that 
information and made some training decisions based on that 
information 
there is always some confusion in the reporting of any 
military operation and i didnt want to add to it russ 
statement said 
he added when i look back at what has transpired it is 
evident that more detail should have been forwarded 
the report on the performance of the f117a called stealth for 
