a prosecutor urged jurors today to convict 
raymond buckey of child molestation but said the decision must be 
based on more than the testimony of three children 
i would not ask you to convict the defendant in this case 
based solely on the testimony of the children said deputy 
district attorney pam ferrero in her closing argument 
the childrens testimony is corroborated by the circumstantial 
evidence in this case she added 
she told jurors they should look at videotapes made during the 
childrens interviews at a child therapy center and read the 
expressions on the childrens faces rather than listening to their 
words to determine whether they were molested 
she said the children had sometimes denied being molested 
because of threats from buckey that the youngsters parents would 
be killed if they told what had happened to them at the mcmartin 
preschool in manhattan beach 
this particular case boils down to credibility the 
prosecutor said who do you believe if you believe the children 
then the people have proved their case beyond a reasonable doubt 
however she conceded that the childrens testimony was not 
clear on all points and required corroboration she also warned 
jurors that the three girls who testified during the trial had been 
through so many different interviews and witnessstand appearances 
during the past seven years that their testimony might be 
contradictory 
buckey is being tried for the second time on eight counts of 
child molestation the first trial ended jan 18 with buckeys 
mother acquitted of all charges and buckey acquitted of 40 counts 
of molestation jurors deadlocked on 13 other charges against 
buckey however and prosecutors refiled eight of those counts 
what would you be able to relate to after this number of 
testimonies and interviews ms ferrero asked she said some of 
the children were telling the story for the umpteenth millionth 
time 
