the chief of the tactical air command 
intensified training for stealth fighterbomber crews after 
learning that they had missed their targets in panama but did not 
pass the information on to the pentagon a spokesman said monday 
col ron sconyers a spokesman for gen robert d russ 
commented after the new york times reported that a classified air 
force report concluded russ the commands chief knew of the 
failures by the radarevading aircraft but did not tell his 
superiors 
general russ eventually knew that the aircraft had missed its 
targets but not early on sconyers said he said it was at least 
10 to 15 days after the operation when the general found out russ 
made training decisions based on that information he said 
but he said the general did not think it was up to him to make a 
report to the pentagon because he was basically just a supplier 
of aircraft he is not part of the operational chain of command 
the tactical air command is responsible for tactics and training 
for the f117a called stealth for its ability to avoid radar 
detection 
because he wasnt part of the operational chain of command and 
doesnt receive or generate operational reports he made the 
assumption that that would be done through the operational chain of 
command sconyers said 
there was never any intent on gen russs part to withhold 
information the spokesman said he added in hindsight he 
would have done it a little differently 
russ in a statement given to the times in response to two 
questions said there is always some confusion in the reporting 
of any military operation and i didnt want to add to it when 
look back at what has transpired it is evident that more detail 
should have been forwarded 
the times said a lack of information had initially led defense 
