<TEXT>
black workers nationwide 
stayed home monday in a strike to protest black factional fighting 
that has killed thousands labor groups said up to 3 million blacks 
took part 
black absenteeism in the major cities of johannesburg pretoria 
durban and port elizabeth ranged from 50 percent to more than 90 
percent according to estimates by police labor and management 
trade unionists reported one death in a township outside durban 
and several injuries in scattered clashes around the country 
also police said an 8yearold boy was fatally shot and three 
people injured when an officer fired at a mob stoning his vehicle 
it was not immediately clear if the attack in a township southeast 
of johannesburg was related to the strike 
in most places however the strike was peaceful 
no precise figures were available on the number of participants 
but labor groups claimed up to 3 million took part 
the congress of south african trade unions which joined the 
african national congress in organizing the oneday strike 
estimated that up to 3 million workers stayed home 
the response from our people demonstrates unequivocally the 
extent of mass support for the programs and policies of our 
organizations the labor group said in a statement 
the anc is the countrys leading group fighting the white 
governments system of racial discrimination the group whose 
deputy president is nelson mandela has denounced the deadly feuds 
between black factions saying they detract from the struggle 
against apartheid 
the south african chamber of business estimated mondays work 
stoppage cost the country almost 300 million in lost productivity 
the anc called the walkout to protest black factional fighting 
in the eastern province of natal the fighting has claimed about 
4000 lives since 1986 
the anc has demanded the whiteled government end a state of 
emergency in natal and disband local zulu police 
several black groups opposed mondays strike the opponents 
included the inkatha movement the conservative zulu organization 
that has been fighting anc supporters for supremacy in natal 
black groups have become increasingly hostile to one another in 
recent months as they compete for supporters and influence 
hundreds of blacks have died in factional fighting since president 
fw de klerk legalized dozens of antiapartheid organizations in 
february 
in natal at least twothirds of the black workforce took part 
in the strike according to congress of trade unions police put 
the participation figure at 60 percent in natal and said many 
people were intimidated into staying home 
people wanting to go to work have been prevented from doing 
so said mangosuthu buthelezi the leader of inkatha and the zulu 
homeland he accused the protest organizers of political 
thuggery 
police reported monday that three blacks had been killed in the 
latest factional fights in natal during the weekend 
authorities made efforts to break the strike monday 
