<TEXT>
congressional backers of the v22 osprey are 
touting an internal pentagon report on the tiltrotor aircraft as 
conclusive evidence against defense secretary dick cheneys plans 
to scrap the plane 
the pentagons arguments about the high cost of the osprey are 
no longer credible rep curt weldon rpa said monday in 
response to the draft report delivered to lawmakers friday 
the congressmans comments came one day after sen arlen 
specter rpa released excerpts of the 1200page report by the 
pentagons own think tank the institute for defense analysis 
the cat is out of the bag now specter said and there can 
be no more stalling or equivocating by the defense department about 
the merits and costeffectiveness of the osprey 
citing budget constraints cheney last year proposed canceling 
the program to buy the osprey an aircraft that takes off like a 
helicopter but flies like a plane 
lobbying by lawmakers from texas and pennsylvania the osprey 
is built by boeing helicopter of lester pa and bell helicopter 
textron of fort worth texas was fierce with weldon and specter 
two of the most vocal supporters 
congress eventually put off a final decision and earmarked 255 
million for research and development of the aircraft in the defense 
budget for 1990 
cheney again called for terminating the program in 1991 arguing 
that a mix of ch46 ch53 and uh60 helicopters would be a cheaper 
alternative the proposal touched off another round of persistent 
lobbying that is not expected to end until congress approves the 
defense budgets later this year 
the draft report which congress called for last july said the 
original plan to buy and operate 502 of the aircraft for the marine 
corps would cost 33 billion in fiscal 1988 dollars 
the alternative of a mix of ch53 and ch60 helicopters would 
cost about 24 billion 
by limiting the osprey program to 24 billion or 356 aircraft 
the report said the v22s speed range and survivability 
advantages could enable even the fleet to be more effective 
sometimes significantly more and other times slightly more than 
all of the proposed helicopter alternatives in each of the four 
marine missions examined 
that assessment is certain to be used by backers of the aircraft 
in their longrunning battle with the defense department over funds 
