<TEXT>
a national conservation group declared the 
decadeold alaska lands act a failure on monday and called on 
congress to begin monitoring the protection of the states national 
parks and wildlife refuges 
opponents of this law have done everything they could to turn 
a resource protection act into a resource development act said 
george frampton jr president of the wilderness society its 
time americans had a look at whats being done to the 39 percent of 
the federal lands that lie within alaska its not a pretty 
picture 
during the past six months the wilderness society has studied 
the effectiveness of the alaska national interest lands 
conservation act signed in 1980 by president jimmy carter to 
preserve the states wildlife areas 
the act was hailed by conservationists as one of the most 
ambitious preservation initiatives ever enacted it set aside 1043 
million acres of national parks wildlife refuges and other 
protected areas in alaska 
in its study the society found that many of the lands that 
supposedly were being protected are facing serious threats 
we hope this report and the work that underlies it will serve 
as a basis for congressional oversight frampton said at a news 
conference called to release the 61page report 
the most serious threat to public lands in alaska is oil and gas 
development in the arctic national wildlife refuge according to 
the report 
there is less than oneinfive chance that a commercially 
viable oil field lies beneath the refuges fabled coastal plain 
it says if there is such a field the most likely annual yield 
would satisfy less than two percent of us oil demand 
the arctic refuge is located in the northeastern corner of 
alaska the refuges center of wildlife activity is a 
16millionacre coastal plain a roughly 25milewide area framed 
by the ocean and the brooks range 
a provision in the alaska lands act directed the us park 
service and the us fish and wildlife service to review all lands 
within alaskas national parks and wildlife refuges to see if they 
qualify for wilderness protection 
congress can designate public land as wilderness if it hasnt 
been developed that designation means the land can never be 
developed 
under the act the interior department was to complete that 
review in 1985 and the president was to recommend to congress which 
areas ought to receive protection the interior department still 
hasnt conducted the wilderness review 
society officials said the bush administration isnt seriously 
following the acts mandate to protect wildlife but is trying to 
preserve development options whenever possible 
in alaska there has been no significant change from the 
policy of the reagan administration said frampton were stuck 
in the crack of a broken record 
excessive logging in the 169millionacre tongass national 
forest is another serious threat society officials said 
the act set a minimum harvest of 45 billion board feet from 
tongass in one decade congress gave the forest service 400 
million to build logging roads and administer the harvest program 
and the forest service sold the trees to private industry 
however the price the forest service got was so low it lost 73 
cents for every taxpayer dollar paid said bennett beach a 
spokesman for the society 
the wilderness society wants congress to pass the tongass timber 
reform act in a form close to the bill passed by the house last 
july society officials said the version approved june 13 by the 
senate needs to be strengthened which is expected to go to 
conference after the august recess 
</TEXT>
