<TEXT>
east germans plunged into capitalism monday 
with west german money in their pockets strikes by thousands of 
worried workers and happy housewives buying bananas chocolate and 
fresh meat 
it was the first day of business after east germany merged its 
economy and social welfare system with west germanys on sunday 
officially ending east germanys 40year experiment with a 
communist system 
gerhard pannier a worried coal dealer said were rolling 
into a dark tunnel without even knowing therell be an engine to 
pull us out 
full political unification is expected in december 
with widespread layoffs expected in east germany there was 
immediate labor unrest 
a spokesman for the powerful ig metall union claimed during a 
rally that up to 30000 workers briefly downed tools in warning 
strikes in about 10 factories around east berlin 
karlheinz graffenberger a union leader said 3000 workers 
struck a locomotive factory in hennigsdorf where the rally was 
held 
one worker kerstin arendt 21 said she makes 640 marks about 
390 a month takehome pay with 600 marks you dont get very 
far she said 
other strikes were reported at the ludwigsfelde car parts plant 
south of berlin and a steel factory in brandenburg workers 
demanded higher pay and improved working conditions east germanys 
adn news agency reported 
graffenberger said they also wanted job security 
east berlin coal dealers used their trucks to blockade loading 
points at four locations to protest the end of state subsidies on 
brown coal the nations most important source of energy 
economists have predicted up to one third of east germanys 
8000 businesses may fail when the full force of west german 
competition decends on their inefficient production methods 
the number of unemployed east germans rose to 150000 from 
100000 a month earlier east german labor minister regine 
hildebrandt said in a radio interview monday 
experts have predicted up to 4 million people could end up out 
of work in this nation of 166 million 
adn said the robotron computer company was offering courses in 
office automation and business management to jobless east germans 
employees of robotron which used to be east germanys 
hightechnology showcase are taking part of the course themselves 
to become familiar with western management techniques adn said 
heiko lehmann 26 a research physicist working for a lamp 
factory grumbled first of all ill lose my job then ill live 
on 700 marks a month and i dont know how ill get by on that 
but he said he was optimistic about ultimately landing a new job 
his 424 benefit is 75 percent of his lastearned wage 
west germany sent 25 billion marks 151 billion from its 
national banks cash reserves to cover the initial phase of 
economic unification east germans could change some of their 
worthless east german marks for west german marks at a 11 rate as 
the country swung over to a capitalist system 
on international markets the west german mark remained strong 
and even made slight gains against the us dollar 
to east berlin shoppers unification meant that chiquita 
bananas tuborg beer and milka chocolate were available at the 
corner grocery 
buying those items used to involve what one housewife called 
exhausting trips to west berlin before the berlin wall came 
down in november there was no way shed have gotten them at all 
housewives praised the lean and more appetizing meat now on sale 
some things are cheaper some are more expensive but on 
average it should be ok said dietmar bauer as he emerged 
from a grocery store frustrated by a gargantuan checkout line he 
bought nothing 
salaries in east germany are less than half the average in west 
germany but east german rents and other basic items will be kept 
low for a while to help compensate 
on the whole prices of most foodstuffs and consumer goods were 
about equal to those in west germany 
but because east germany has ended all government subsidies on 
food the price of a roll tripled from eight to 24 pfennigs 515 
cents the price of milk more than doubled adn said 
trade minister sybille reider toured shops belonging to the 
konsum chain on east berlins outskirts and accused the formerly 
stateowned enterprise of shamefully abusing its monopoly in 
the countryside adn reported 
ms reider found a konsum store in beelitz southwest of berlin 
charging 229 marks 138 for a halfpound of butter as opposed 
to 179 marks 108 in areas where competition exists 
she complained of halfempty shelves and said whatever 
east german produce was for sale was miserably wrapped and of very 
poor quality 
also monday the elevated railway system known as the sbahn 
resumed services between east and west berlin for the first time 
since the berlin wall went up in 1961 
sbahn authorities plan to reopen six more crossborder lines 
but major repairs to stations and tracks are needed before they 
become operational 
