the food and drug administration on monday 
announced stronger warnings against use of overthecounter aspirin 
products by women in the last three months of pregnancy unless 
directed by a physician 
the agency said the stronger warning on labels is being required 
because aspirin can affect fetal circulation and uterine 
contraction 
manufacturers have one year to add the stronger warning to all 
oral and rectal overthecounter products containing aspirin the 
fda said 
the warning must read 
it is especially important not to use aspirin during the last 
three months of pregnancy unless specifically directed to do so by 
a doctor because it may cause problems in the unborn child or 
complications during delivery 
aspirin products now carry a general warning that says 
as with any drug if you are pregnant or nursing a baby seek 
the advice of a health professional before using this product 
an advisory panel of medical experts had recommended the 
stronger warning 
a similar thirdtrimester pregnancy warning is already required 
on nonprescription products containing the painreliever ibuprofen 
the regulation is to be published in the federal register on 
thursday 
