more than half of the nations cities and 
towns expect spending to exceed revenues in their current budget 
year and twothirds of the municipalities say budget crunches are 
worse than a year ago according to a survey released monday 
the national league of cities survey of 576 communities said the 
budget pressures are greatest in the northeast where the regional 
economy is slumping five of six cities and towns surveyed in that 
region reported that their financial problems were worse than a 
year ago 
a majority of communities in the south the midwest and the west 
also reported that budget strains were greater this year 
leaders of the organization whose membership is open to cities 
and towns with populations of at least 10000 said a major factor 
in the growing municipal budget problems is the lack of help from 
washington 
we see this as a crucial time for national leadership said 
donald borut the leagues executive director 
as president bush and congressional leaders seek an agreement on 
a deficitreduction plan likely to include some form of higher 
taxes the survey showed many cities also were looking for 
additional revenues 
fortyone percent of those surveyed have raised local property 
taxes 76 percent have increased fees and other charges the league 
of cities said 
just over half 51 percent reduced the rate of spending 
growth in their budgets and 39 percent contracted out certain 
services in an attempt to cut costs the survey found 
borut called the results a warning signal about stresses on 
our local revenue systems about our ability to maintain important 
services and about the consequences of unfunded mandates and the 
continuing withdrawal of federal and state participation in 
providing vital services 
the leagues board of directors plans to meet with house ways 
and means committee chairman dan rostenkowski dill next week 
before the organization makes its suggestions on deficitreduction 
priorities 
