<TEXT>
a federal research group recommended on monday 
a more liberal policy on truck weights that it said could save 43 
billion a year in transport costs and cost railroads 750 million 
in lost revenue 
the national research council committee said all states should 
be given the option of exempting some trucks from a federal limit 
of 80000 pounds on the nations interstate highways it also 
recommended changes in the rules for bridge use that would allow 
heavier concrete mixers dump trucks and other trucks with shorter 
wheelbases 
the weight exemptions would be on the condition that they 
include fees to cover pavement and bridge wear said the committee 
which is made up of transportation experts from universities the 
industry and government the research council is linked to the 
national academy of sciences and the national academy of 
engineering 
the committee report recommends that heavy trucks still be 
restricted to designated routes comply with all other federal 
weight restrictions and comply with strict safety standards 
the exemptions would still be up to individual states but the 
report said it was not fair to prevent about half the states from 
allowing exemptions while the others who had exemptions before the 
current law can keep theirs 
if all states adopted the exemptions annual transportation 
savings for truckers could total 19 billion because of the use of 
more productive vehicles the report said this would lower costs 
by 16 percent attracting 750 million in rail business it said 
savings in trucking costs from a new bridge formula could total 
24 billion the committee said 
the report requested by congress brought praise from the 
trucking industry which estimates its services at 240 billion 
annually 
we feel the suggestions would have a great value to the 
economy as a whole and will make significant differences in the 
competitive situation of the united states as compared to the rest 
of the world said john reith policy director for the american 
trucking associations 
he said the report is the result of two years of research 
a rail industry spokesman said he had not seen the report but 
was concerned that any nationwide increase in truck sizes and 
weights could have a serious impact on railroads 
dan lang vice president of the association of american 
railroads said trucks pay only about half their share of highway 
maintenance costs and fail to pay other highway expenses including 
the social cost of pollution and added traffic 
if youre going to go out and upset the status quo this way 
you should really take another look at all the costs associated 
lang said 
the committee report did not call for substantially heavier 
trucks over 80000 pounds and did not address truck lengths said 
its chairman lester a hoel of the university of virginia 
we simply recommended a level playing field for fairness to 
give all states the option of imlementing a permit program said 
hoel 
federal law currently restricts gross vehicle weight to 80000 
pounds with a limit of 20000 pounds per axle and 34000 pounds 
for tandem axles bridgecrossing requirements are based on a 
formula which includes weight the number of axles and their 
distance apart 
the report recommends that axle weight limits be maintained 
which means the heavier trucks would not cause significant changes 
in pavement wear it said 
the committee concluded that it was arbitrary and 
inequitable to allow some states to give exemptions but said it 
would cost about 8 billion to remove all exempted vehicles from 
the highway this would result in more accidents pollution and 
traffic because it would take more smaller trucks to replace them 
the study said 
it said the current formula for bridge use is an overly 
cautious limit on weights for shorter trucks 
</TEXT>
