soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev on monday 
defended policies that led to the ouster of hardline communist 
rulers across eastern europe saying the region is ridding itself 
of stalinism 
big changes are under way in eastern europe gorbachev said 
in his keynote speech to the 28th congress of the soviet communist 
party in the kremlin 
and when it is said it is the failure of socialism we ask 
in reply what kind of socialism the kind that was in fact a 
stalinist version well we are are getting rid of that 
ourselves he said 
the stalinist model of socialism is being replaced by a civil 
society of free men and women gorbachev declared 
many hardline soviet communists have questioned the wisdom of 
gorbachevs relaxation of controls over its allies in the warsaw 
pact military alliance 
gorbachev told his fellow party members monday that his policies 
had allowed change to occur peacefully in eastern europe except 
for romanias violent revolution in december little blood was shed 
as communists rulers were overthrown elsewhere 
every east bloc communist leader in power during the last soviet 
communist party congress in 1986 was ousted by this spring 
in hungary and poland the changes came at the ballot box 
peaceful revolutions swept away the old orders in east germany and 
czechoslovakia the communists in bulgaria ousted longtime rulers 
under the pressure of popular protests 
the upheaval was produced in part by gorbachevs social and 
economic reforms in the soviet union eastern european communist 
reformers and opposition activists quickly sensed the significance 
of the policies of glasnost and perestroika that gorbachev put into 
effect shortly after he took power in 1985 
in addition gorbachevs tacit renunciation of the brezhnev 
doctrine accelerated reform in eastern europe that policy 
outlined in 1968 limited the sovereignty of moscows warsaw pact 
allies and sanctioned the use of force to preserve socialism 
