tragedy and the hajj the pilgrimage to mecca that every moslem 
is expected to make at least once are no strangers and mondays 
disaster was the second in three years in which a great number of 
pilgrims lost their lives 
in 1987 clashes with saudi security forces in mecca killed 402 
people during the hajj 275 of them iranians hundreds were injured 
the year before the saudis had confiscated large quantities of 
explosives from members of the iranian contingent to mecca 
in 1979 religious extremists seized the grand mosque in mecca 
and held it for two weeks before saudi forces stormed it more than 
250 people were killed and saudi authorities later beheaded 63 more 
saudi arabia restricted the number of pilgrims and later broke 
off diplomatic ties with iran after the 1987 carnage the most 
serious of a series of incidents during pilgrimages since irans 
islamic revolution in 1979 
the incidents were fired by iranian efforts to politicize the 
hajj and encourage other moslem nations to seize shrines at mecca 
and medina from the control of the kingdoms saud royal family 
last month the saudi government said iranians were welcome to 
take part in this years islamic pilgrimage to mecca but would not 
be allowed to demonstrate it was an antiamerican demonstration 
that led to the 1987 slaughter 
iran denied in september 1989 that it was involved in two bomb 
blasts in mecca two months earlier and tehransupported terrorists 
vowed to avenge saudi arabias execution of 16 shiite moslems 
convicted of setting the explosions 
the bombs exploded as thousands of people took part in the 
annual pilgrimage to islams most sacred city killing one person 
and injuring 16 
the explosions erupted as hundreds of thousands of pilgrims were 
praying and walking around the kaaba islams holiest shrine 
inside the grand mosque 
the attacks were believed connected to the centuriesold feud 
between sunni and shiite moslems 
every moslem sunni or shiite has a duty to make the pilgrimage 
to mecca the birthplace of the 7th century prophet mohammed and 
to medina where mohammed is buried 
sunnis and shiites disagree about who should have succeeded 
mohammed who founded islam 
iran which has an overwhelming majority of shiites among its 
nearly 50 million people had been urging moslems to seize mecca 
and medina 
last year an estimated 18 million moslems from more than 80 
nations went on the annual pilgrimage an estimated 2 million 
people attended this year 
