a federal judge says a town may arrest 
people who sleep on the beach or in their cars in beachside 
neighborhoods rejecting a challenge to an ordinances 
constitutionality 
the law for the town of westerly doesnt involve a fundamental 
right us district judge francis j boyle said in a ruling 
handed down friday and released monday 
the state american civil liberties union challenged the law on 
behalf of two connecticut men arrested in july 1988 the case was 
expanded to a class action covering 268 people arrested during the 
past three years 
the aclu said enforcement was unfair because rhode island 
residents were given summonses and released while outofstaters 
were jailed unless they appeared before a justice of the peace 
pleaded no contest and paid a 20 fine 
boyle ruled that westerly had a legitimate interest in treating 
outofstate residents differently because if they fled after 
release there was no way to bring them back to court on the 
misdemeanor charge 
the aclu also argued that the law discriminated against those 
who could not find lodging here during the busy tourist season and 
made them drive out of the area when dangerously tired 
westerly police chief mark s champlin contended the nearly 
30yearold ordinance was needed to reduce a rash of crimes in 
beachside neighborhoods 
by preventing persons from camping on westerlys beaches and 
parking lots without proper amenities and sanitary facilities the 
town protects important governmental interests boyle said 
he rejected what he called the plaintiffs contention that the 
constitution of the united states provides them with an assurance 
of an evenings lodging in westerly 
westerly is about 50 miles southeast of providence 
