<TEXT>
a jury on monday began deliberating the case of a 
christian science couple accused of involuntary manslaughter for 
using prayer instead of medicine to try to treat their sick 
2yearold son 
the jury in the suffolk county superior court trial of david and 
ginger twitchell both 34 began deliberations after closing 
arguments by defense attorney rikki klieman and special prosecutor 
john kiernan 
klieman said the case against his clients was one of 
speculation exaggeration and distortion 
kiernan said the twitchells must be held accountable for not 
seeking medical help for their son robyn who died in april 1986 
after a fiveday illness an autopsy showed he suffered from a 
bowel obstruction 
i dont suggest for a moment these parents intended to kill 
their child kiernan told jurors but they intentionally did 
things that caused his death 
klieman conceded that the twitchells made a mistake but said 
they didnt deserve to be convicted 
the jury hearing the case in the city that is home to the 
christian science churchs headquarters began deliberations late 
in the afternoon after instructions from judge sandra hamlin 
during closing arguments the defense and the prosecution 
returned to themes presented in two months of testimony by medical 
experts emergency personnel christian science practitioners and 
the twitchells former neighbors 
key issues have been the severity of robyns symptoms his time 
of death his parents actions in calling in christian science 
practitioners and whether their church allows medical treatment 
when prayer fails 
klieman made an emotional appeal to the jury to reject the 
notion that the twitchells were uncaring parents who callously 
treated robyns dead body like garbage 
she reiterated that witnesses who saw robyn from april 3 to 
april 7 said the boy was clearly sick but that his life did not 
appear to be threatened 
klieman disputed the prosecution claim that robyns bowel 
obstruction which was due to a birth defect could have been 
easily diagnosed and treated rather the bowel can twist and 
untwist making diagnosis difficult she said 
if it can fool a doctor it can fool any parent and it 
certainly can fool parents who rely on spiritual healing because it 
gets worse it gets better it gets worse it gets better 
klieman said 
kiernan said parents have a millenniumold obligation to protect 
their children 
what he termed the twitchells unabashed unbridled 
arrogance made the obviously suffering little boy a martyr to 
their belief that prayer alone could heal 
this little boy was sacrificed for his own parents 
intellectual purity he said 
describing robyn as moaning in pain kiernan gestured at the 
twitchells saying how could they sit there and not do anything 
how could they not call for a doctor 
as they have through much of the trial the twitchells sat still 
and held hands david twitchell had testified earlier his wife did 
not take the stand 
the twitchells now live in new york with their two other 
children 
