<TEXT>
a federal judge has ruled in favor of 
prison administrators who put an inmate writer in solitary 
confinement after he criticized the warden in print 
articles about matters within a prison can create a danger of 
violence or at least threats of violence and can weaken the 
staffs control of the prison said us district judge charles 
legge 
in the ruling june 26 legge said the us bureau of prisons 
security concerns justified regulations that prohibited inmates 
from acting as reporters from being paid for newspaper articles or 
from writing bylined articles for outside newspapers 
outside newspaper reporting by prisoners can cause rifts within 
a prison improperly focus attention on individual inmates create 
divided loyalties and turn the writer into a big wheel with 
disproportionate notoriety and influence legge said 
the ruling is not binding on other courts us attorney william 
mcgivern whose office defended the regulations said the 52page 
decision should be persuasive in future cases 
legge lifted his march 1989 order that prohibited enforcement of 
the regulations against dannie martin a convicted bank robber who 
has written more than 40 bylined essays on prison life and 
conditions for the san francisco chronicle since 1986 
martins articles from the federal prison in lompoc had been 
praised by the parole board and had not prompted any disciplinary 
