<DOCNO> AP900702-0190 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the cost to human health is harder to assess 
the government has never acknowledged any human health damage 
caused by emissions from its plants or by radiation releases from 
atomic bomb tests in the desert southwest but increasing numbers 
of americans are going to court seeking compensation on grounds 
that chronic exposure to radiation caused illness and death even 
at levels the government considers safe 
bruce h deboskey a denver lawyer for some workers at the rocky 
flats plutonium processing plant says relatives of workers who 
died of cancer feel cheated by the federal government 
the widows of these workers who gave their lives to build 
these bombs are deeply embittered deboskey says theres a 
human tragedy here 
also at risk were thousands of uranium miners who dug out the 
bomb material in unventilated shafts in new mexico arizona utah 
and colorado from the late 1940s to the mid1960s when mining 
stopped because the government had stockpiled all it needed 
of the estimated 15000 men who worked the mines about 450 have 
died of lung cancer five times the number expected in a similar 
size group of american men according to the national institute of 
occupational safety and health 
congress is now trying to make some amends in june the house 
passed a bill to establish a 100 million trust to compensate 
families of miners with radiationinduced illness as well as 
certain cancer victims in nevada utah and arizona who were exposed 
to fallout from aboveground nuclear testing from 1951 to 1962 the 
senate is expected to approve the bill president bush opposes it 
scientists have not yet determined conclusively whether 
accidental releases of radioactivity from nuclear weapons plants 
are a health threat nor are they yet sure of the risk posed by 
chronic exposure of workers to low levels of radiation 
until the mid1980s these issues were secondary production was 
king secrecy its serf 
things having to do with atomic weapons are born secret 
says j carson mark who spent 27 years designing nuclear weapons 
at los alamos national laboratory in new mexico and is now retired 
clyde hopkins remembers the mindset in the early 1950s when he 
was a production control worker at the oak ridge y12 plant which 
used tons of mercury to separate lithium for use as a fuel source 
in thermonuclear warheads 
the pressure was intense to come up with weapons components on 
a shortterm basis he says people back in those days didnt 
even think about the environment they thought about getting the 
doggone work out to support the countrys nuclear stockpile 
i can remember days when people were walking around with lots 
of mercury on the floor you kept operating because you wanted that 
product to come out so the emphasis then was on production the 
thought that we had mercury leaking on the floor obviously working 
its way down through the concrete into the ground it wasnt 
thought about back then 
hopkins thinks about it a lot now he is president of martin 
marietta energy systems which is locked in negotiations with the 
energy department over its financial and legal liability for 
failing to meet state and federal environmental laws 
oak ridge was not alone in its approach to meeting bomb 
production schedules 
cleve anderson recalls fighting against a productionfirst 
mentality while he headed a committee studying longrange waste 
management at hanford in the late 1950s hanford was the main 
producer of plutonium the most lethal element known for use in 
nuclear bombs although today its nine reactors are shut down 
at hanford we had been indoctrinated thoroughly that the 
nations survival depended on what we were doing that nothing was 
more important to national security than getting ever more 
plutonium anything else that might interfere was secondary he 
said 
in a classified report written in december 1958 for general 
electric co which was running hanford under a government 
contract anderson urged that more money be spent to develop safer 
disposal methods for radioactive wastes he wrote the 
probability of the superiority of alternate methods of waste 
disposal has long been recognized but the pressing problems of 
weapons production precluded any but the most cursory 
examinations of these alternatives 
he said his report was shelved years later he had to file a 
request under the freedom of information act to obtain a copy 
today hanford is considered the most extensively contaminated 
piece of land in the united states perhaps in the world 
the governments own advisers were sounding the alarm on nuclear 
waste as early as 1955 in that year the national academy of 
sciences formed a committee to advise the atomic energy commission 
on waste disposal 
the committee concluded in late 1955 that dumping radioactive 
wastes directly into the ground probably involves unacceptable 
longterm risks to the environment yet such practices continued 
for more three decades 
hopkins the martin marietta manager at oak ridge says id 
be surprised if officials there were told prior to the 1980s that 
dumping wastes directly into the ground carried the risk of serious 
environmental damage 
if they had i dont think wed have done it he said 
regardless of the reasons the hazards posed by huge 
accumulations of nuclear wastes now represent a technological 
challenge for america unlike any it has faced since the dawn of the 
atomic age 
weve scratched the surface says duffy the energy 
department waste czar we know the problems we dont know the 
solutions 
one of the least understood problems is how much of the nuclear 
graveyards can be excavated or treated without putting workers at 
unacceptable risk 
frank l parker who headed oak ridge national laboratorys 
radioactive waste management research in the late 1950s and early 
1960s and now teaches environmental engineering at vanderbilt 
university in nashville tenn says the country will have to 
accept that some nuclear wastes are too dangerous to remove 
the number of deaths youre going to incur to clean it up will 
dwarf the number who would be killed if you left it alone he 
says 
