<TEXT>
 
oak ridge tenn ap for more than 30 years the national 
academy of sciences has been sounding warnings about the handling 
of radioactive materials at the nations nuclear weapons facilities 
a report to the government in 1958 cited the academys 
continuing concern about the disposal of intermediate and 
lowlevel waste liquids in seepage pits at oak ridge national 
laboratory because they contaminate the environment 
for several years the academy urged the government to crack down 
on the waste management problems of the private companies that run 
all the weapons plants 
in a 1966 report summarizing 11 years of recommendations on this 
issue the national academy said it had become commonplace for the 
plant operators to use the cheapest methods of waste disposal even 
though these carried large environmental risks 
such methods represent a concept of easy disposal that has had 
and will continue to have great appeal to operators but we fear 
that continuation of the practices eventually will create hazards 
that will be extremely difficult and expensive to eliminate the 
report said 
any compromise with safety for the sake of economy could lead 
in the long run to mushrooming of waste disposal into the most 
costly item in the use of nuclear power 
as with most weapons plant documentation from that period the 
national academy reports were not made public at the time they were 
submitted to the atomic energy commission a predecessor agency to 
the presentday energy department 
</TEXT>
