oak ridge tenn ap the full cost of 45 years of nuclear 
bomb production wont be known for decades but already in subtle 
ways the social toll can be seen 
along quiet bethel valley road inside the boundaries of the oak 
ridge nuclear weapons compound stands the oneroom woodframe new 
bethel baptist church 
behind the boardedup building is a stone monument nearly as 
tall as the church roof with an engraving that reads erected in 
memory of new bethel baptist church 
opened 1851 closed 1942 it reads adding for explanation 
that the sermons stopped when the government took over bethel 
valley and thousands of acres around it to build parts and 
materials for the atomic bombs used in world war ii 
the weapons plants are still here so is the church if only as 
a whitewashed reminder of times past times when the tiny towns of 
wheat robertsville elza and scarboro had their own churches 
their own stores their own school their own tobacco and corn 
farmers their own histories their own hopes for the future times 
before the bomb builders wiped them off the map 
the new bethel baptist church has been spared but today it 
stands empty and alone except for piles of trash visible inside 
through its few unboarded windows and several dozen gravestones in 
a grassy cemetery at the back of the church grounds 
two signs are nailed to a cedar tree beside the church one 
white and wooden says simply new bethel followed by the sign 
of the cross below it a red metal sign of an obviously newer 
vintage says area closed to hunters 
</TEXT>
