<TEXT>
 
editors note the 40000 indians living on reservations in 
upstate new york are clinging to their traditional culture despite 
the encroachment of modern civilization but conflict with the 
white mans world sometimes erupts in violence and gunfire as 
evidenced by the recent shooting down of a national guard 
helicopter 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
centuries after the 
legendary hiawatha paddled the waters of onondaga lake with the 
great peacemaker to unite warring indian tribes the six nations of 
the iroquois confederacy endures 
onondaga lake is now so polluted by industrial effluent that the 
fish are inedible and the shoreline is dominated by the modern 
skyline of the city of syracuse yet just a few miles away chief 
leon shenandoah presides over confederacy meetings in the 
traditional longhouse and performs religious ceremonies dating back 
to hiawathas time 
the observances symbolize the dogged manner in which the tribes 
of the iroquois have kept their culture alive despite the 
encroachment of modern civilization 
we still have our own way of life our own government 
shenandoah says we didnt change much im still doing my 
ceremonies 
the confederacy is a nation within a nation issuing its own 
passports operating gambling casinos in a state where they are 
illegal taking advantage of tax breaks to profit in the sale of 
such things as cigarettes and gasoline 
some iroquois have withdrawn into armed enclaves to escape the 
white mans culture others have embraced it and still others have 
found a way to prosper while retaining their distinctive way of 
life 
what is remarkable about the iroquois is that they have 
survived as a coherent culture so long after coming into contact 
with us says jan wojcik humanities professor at clarkson 
university in potsdam ny eightyfive percent of the indian 
cultures are gone there are very few left the iroquois are very 
strong very healthy 
wojcik says in fact that the mohawks on the st regis indian 
reservation in northern new york are very prosperous compared 
with indians on most other reservations in the country 
they have jobs there are good houses people drive cars 
wojcik says they are almost indistinguishable from the 
middleclass mainstream 
there are about 40000 indians living throughout upstate new 
york about eight times as many as when henry hudson sailed the 
half moon up the hudson river nearly 400 years ago 
that journey signaled the start of centuries of uneasy relations 
between indians and white men in upstate new york 
the iroquois confederacy was founded between 500 and 1000 years 
ago to prevent bloody conflicts among the senecas mohawks 
cayugas onondagas and oneidas the tuscaroras joined the 
confederacy later when they were driven out of north carolina 
the influence of the iroquois waned when the confederacy sided 
with the british in the revolutionary war under a confused and 
still disputed patchwork of treaties in the late 1700s the tribes 
of the iroquois were relegated to reservations as waves of 
nonindian immigrants settled across upstate new york 
legal title to those lands and whether the reservations embody 
sovereign nations are issues that continue to plague the iroquois 
relations with the state and federal governments theyre also the 
basis of bloody conflicts among tribal members themselves 
on may 1 two mohawks were killed when a dispute over casino 
gambling on the st regis indian reservation along the new 
yorkcanadian border turned into a fierce gun battle between 
proand antigambling factions 
new york and canadian police are still manning armed roadblocks 
on the reservation to prevent further bloodshed 
earlier this year a doctor was wounded when a vermont national 
guard helicopter was brought down by gunfire while flying over the 
ganienkeh indian territory in northern new york that prompted a 
tense standoff between heavily armed militant mohawks and state 
troopers with indians vowing to die for their cause 
the iroquois insist on being treated as an independent nation 
going so far as issuing passports that are recognized by such 
countries as the united states canada and great britain 
yet most police officials believe they have responsibility to 
maintain order on new york reservations and to investigate reports 
of felonies at the same time they know they risk a violent 
reaction by ordering officers onto indian land 
during the standoffs at the ganienkeh indian territory powerful 
automatic weapons were brandished by defiant mohawks who said they 
were ready to take on troopers no arrests have been made in the 
downing of the helicopter 
county sheriffs deputies will not enter the onondaga indian 
reservation without permission of the chiefs even when they are 
pursuing a murder suspect 
sovereignty has its economic advantages indians are exempt from 
state and federal taxes and indian entrepreneurs have made a 
booming business of selling cigarettes and gasoline to outsiders 
who come to the reservation to evade taxes by making the trip to a 
reservation a person can save approximately 3 on each carton of 
cigarettes and 14 cents on each gallon of gasoline 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900702-0195 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
and claiming sovereign exemption from outside laws against 
gambling the oneidas and mohawks have established lucrative 
casinos and bingo parlors on their reservations with tour bus 
service to transport customers in from neighboring cities 
the st regis casinos were particularly popular with canadian 
gamblers 
new york officials insist that some of the gambling is illegal 
and they estimate that the state loses up to 20 million a year in 
taxes due to the indian entrepreneurs 
the word tax is not in our seneca language dennis lay 
president of the seneca indian nation recently argued before state 
lawmakers in albany it is interpreted as being detrimental to 
our survival as a sovereign nation let the seneca nation govern 
ourselves without a taxing scheme created by your government 
lays tribe won a major victory this spring when the city of 
salamanca agreed to a new 80year lease that calls for payments of 
at least 800000 a year to the tribe the agreement includes a 
onetime grant of 60 million to the senecas to make up for past 
injustices against the tribe 
one of the reasons the iroquois have endured so well is by 
taking advantage of economic opportunities says clarkson 
universitys wojcik 
the iroquois especially the mohawks have earned a reputation 
in the highpaying high steel work on new york city 
skyscrapers the indians who display great balance agility and an 
apparent fearlessness of heights often share small apartments in 
new york city during the week and travel back to their upstate 
reservations on weekends 
iroquois life is full of other seeming contradictions between 
the traditional indian culture and modern america when the 
militant mohawks at ganienkeh were manning their barricades they 
issued statements to the media via a fax machine harold tarbell a 
traditionalist chief at st regis wears his hair in a traditional 
braid while sporting pleated pants and pierre cardin sunglasses 
despite outside pressures shenandoah who has been the iroquois 
chief of chiefs for two decades insists the traditional indian way 
of life is strong 
tom porter a mohawk chief at st regis says i think 
practically every mohawk to some degree follows the traditional 
way 
shenandoah is suspicious of white society and governments 
staunchly refusing to accept governmental aid that was not part of 
a treaty 
we accept nothing from the government he says no one 
from the state has any input here 
the longhouse continues to exert a strong influence over the 
iroquois says shenandoah gesturing toward the three churches on 
the onondaga reservation 
you can put all three churches together and well put more 
people in the longhouse shenandoah says 
were not pagan we dont idolize things in our way of life 
the government is the one that idolizes money the creator did not 
create money so we dont pray for money 
the land the iroquois control directly has been whittled away 
since the revolution 
the onondagas mohawks senecas tuscaroras and oneidas live on 
reservations scattered around upstate new york where their 
languages are taught to children in indian schools 
the cayugas have no land and have gone to court to reclaim 
property they claim was illegally deeded to the state 180 years ago 
without the necessary approval of congress 
the reason were fighting for land is so we can save our 
culture says cayuga chief frank bonamie we do not have a 
school so we miss out on teaching our children 
the oneidas are down to a 32acre plot in the city of oneida and 
have also gone to court seeking more land the mohawks also have 
land claims pending 
to this day the state of new york dutifully delivers 150 
bushels of salt annually to the onondagas to honor provisions of 
two treaties dating back to 1795 that turned onondaga land into 
what is now syracuse shenandoah does not recognize the salt 
payment 
chief bonamie believes the iroquois culture will endure 
when you sit at the grand council and look around and think 
this has been going on for hundreds of years there is a lot of 
power in that room he says it is an exciting time to be at a 
grand council meeting and feel the strength and power in that 
room 
it might have its ups and downs but i think it will endure 
forever 
</TEXT>
