<DOCNO> AP900702-0196 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
such american 
constitutional concepts as freedom of speech and representational 
government were derived from the iroquois confederacys great law 
some scholars say 
the ancient great law of peace that preceded the us 
constitution by centuries was based on strength through union it 
enunciated such concepts as individual rights as well as checks and 
balances among the various branches of government 
they copied our form of government says onondaga chief leon 
shenandoah who has been the chief of chiefs of the six nations of 
the iroquois confederacy for more than two decades 
according to the oral history of the indians the iroquois 
confederacy was founded 500 to 1000 years ago when the great 
peacemaker and the legendary hiawatha persuaded the senecas 
mohawks cayugas onondagas and oneidas to stop their warring and 
form a union the tuscaroras joined the confederacy later when they 
were driven out of north carolina 
the confederacy survives with the distinction of being the 
oldest league of nations in the world confederacy chiefs still 
gather at the longhouse on the onondaga reservation near syracuse 
ny to interpret the great law 
one of the strongest proponents of the theory of the iroquois 
influence on the us constitution is donald grinde a professor of 
american indian history at the university of california at 
riverside 
benjamin franklin john quincy adams thomas jefferson and james 
madison were some of the founding fathers who were known to discuss 
the iroquois system while they were formulating the us 
constitution grinde says 
the founding fathers for a generation or more before the 
american revolution looked at the iroquois confederacy as an 
alternative to the british model says grinde who has written 
two books on the subject 
they were definitely talking about it 
not all historians agree 
the evidence is flimsy at best says jan wojcik humanities 
professor at clarkson university in potsdam ny wojcik says the 
claim is based on hearsay 
supposedly benjamin franklin listened to them give a 
description of their confederacy before the constitutional 
convention he says in fact he was contemptuous of the 
iroquois and referred to them as savages i dont really think 
there is any direct link that is traceable 
to prove his point grinde cites a book john quincy adams wrote 
a month before the constitutional convention in philadelphia urging 
consideration of the indian government 
their separation of powers is marked with a precision that 
excludes all controversy adams wrote at the time 
in 1776 more than two dozen iroquois chiefs participated in the 
debates over the declaration of independence at the invitation of 
the continental congress the historian said 
the framers referred to the iroquois and the confederacy in 
their debates to create the articles of confederation which 
preceded the constitution grinde says 
its all in the records of the constitutional congress and in 
the correspondence of the delegates grinde says its just 
been ignored but indians especially the iroquois played a key 
role in the constitutional process 
the iroquois also provided the framers of the constitution with 
a model for linking separate governments across a great 
geographical expanse something the european governments did not 
do grinde says 
for centuries the iroquois dominated much of what is now 
upstate new york ironically most of the iroquois sided with the 
british and the confederacy lost much of its power after the 
revolution 
</TEXT>
