editors note the nations growing appetite for fish has 
produced thriving catfish farms in the deep south and trout farms 
in the northwest now cashing in on the trend are farmers in 
appalachia who are growing bass and salmon insted of corn and 
wheat 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
metz wva joshua brickensteins home looks like the other 
rugged wooden dwellings in these treecovered hills of appalachia 
deep in coal country 
but inside he has signs books and even a stainglassed window 
that proclaim fish not coal or cattle is king here 
brickenstein is a farmer a fish farmer his cash crops are 
striped bass coho salmon and tilapia he is one of a growing 
number of landlocked farmers turning to fish as an alternative to 
such traditional crops as corn wheat and hay 
the us department of agriculture says the market for 
farmproduced fish is growing 
the 1990s should be an important decade for growth the 
usda said recently world population gains and limits on wild 
catch from the oceans should increase the demand for aquaculture 
products 
the government says increased fish consumption in the united 
states will be met through more imports and more farmers like 
brickenstein 
david harvey a usda agricultural economist in washington 
dc specializing in aquaculture said about one in every 10 fish 
eaten by americans now comes from fish farms 
aquaculture thrives in states such as mississippi louisiana and 
arkansas where the mississippi river and its delta provides 
excellent conditions for catfish farming 
it also is successful in western states such as idaho and 
montana where natural conditions make it profitable to raise trout 
joseph a marshall associate biology professor at west virginia 
university said the practice is most popular in china where one 
out of every four fish eaten comes from a farm asians first began 
growing their own fish about 4000 years ago 
marshall said fish farming is growing because ocean fishermen 
are finding catches harder to come by 
fish are cheaper to feed than livestock he says it takes up to 
9 pounds of feed for each pound of beef produced compared with up 
to 1 pound of feed for each pound of fish produced he says 
in addition he says many consumers are reluctant to buy 
freshcaught fish for fear of pollution contamination 
you dont know what youre getting when you eat oceancaught 
fish he says you have no idea what the mercury levels are in 
many cases there are no checks for many fish caught out of the 
country 
local restaurants also prefer a good nearby source of fresh 
fish he says 
when stores label fish fresh that only means it hasnt been 
frozen marshall says big stores have weekold fish and they 
call it fresh you can taste the difference 
brickensteins 98acre farm about 80 miles southwest of 
pittsburgh includes two 2000gallon indoor tanks which look like 
aboveground swimming pools and sound like giant aquariums 
the tanks are used to keep young fish alive when winter weather 
sours later maturing fish are transferred to outdoor farm ponds 
where they are submerged in 4by4foot cages that ensure their 
food stays in one place 
brickenstein 62 took up fish farming six years ago after 
retiring as a selfemployed plastics manufacturer in tel aviv 
israel and pittsburgh he also grows raspberries on his farm 
which he admits is more a hobby supplemented by money he 
accumulated as a businessman 
he calculates a prudent fish farmer could net up to 30000 a 
year with fish although he has yet to turn a profit in five years 
as he experiments with different methods of aquaculture 
brickenstein builds his tanks by hand and uses a homemade 
filtering system to clean water pollution created by the fish 
he raises the fish from fingerling stage or when theyre about 
the size of a tadpole he stresses the importance of making sure 
fish get just the right amount of food too much can leave them 
just as dead as too little 
the fish are kept indoors in a building thats something of a 
cross between a henhouse garage and a barn the ponds meanwhile 
are located about a quarter mile from his house and the road 
nestled in the hills and surrounded by rolling green meadows 
scientists say they still arent sure if fish farming hurts the 
environment 
maryland officials are offering up to 15000 in grant money to 
fish farmers who build wastewater treatment facilities 
essentially if you take fish and feed them the excess feed 
turns into a nitrogen product that may eventually turn into 
ammonia which can hurt other fish says brad powers marylands 
aquaculture coordinator 
what were saying is we dont know whether aquaculture is a 
problem what were trying to do is head it off in advance 
still marshall believes the prospects for aquaculture are 
unlimited 
what you make of it is really what you put into it he says 
youve seen farmers who raise scraggly cattle and youve seen 
farmers with sparkling cattle how you manage will determine how 
well you do 
marshall also says aquaculture can be simple for someone who has 
an occasional yen for fresh fish 
you just have to use a little ingenuity he said theres 
nothing saying that if you have an aquarium in your home you cant 
eat the fish 
</TEXT>
