editors note in creating the national parks congress said 
they should be preserved as they were found that meant no new 
critters could be introduced or tolerated on park land but here 
are a bunch of stray horses that some people in missouri would like 
to keep and the park service says must go 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the bands of stray horses that have roamed 
the rugged and beautiful missouri ozarks for more than 20 years are 
heading for the last roundup 
fugitives from farms in the mid1960s they have wandered 
through the wildflowerdotted fields of waisthigh grass and drunk 
from the rivers and springs that flow through the lush forests and 
valleys theyve become as wild as mustangs 
but now the us park service contends the two dozen or so 
animals cant properly fend for themselves and should be captured 
and sold 
the government announced in may that it plans to hire cowboys to 
round up the horses from the 60000 acres of wilderness in the 
ozark national scenic riverways in southern missouri 
it will be a sad day when there are no more wild horses around 
here says rolland smotherman of birch tree who trains and shoes 
horses for a living and often ventures out on horseback with 
friends to observe the strays where else can you go and see wild 
horses except for out west 
smotherman and a number of residents of this sparsely populated 
region located about 150 miles southwest of st louis say the 
horses are thriving in the wild several new foals were seen this 
spring he says 
they believe the animals should be left alone to be enjoyed by 
the public including the thousands of canoeists campers and 
fishermen who flock to the current and jacks fork rivers each year 
those horses wintered fat i guarantee they are healthier than 
ninetenths of the horses most people have around here says 
richard wilkins of mountain view who owns a feed store and seven 
horses 
supporters have gathered about 1000 signatures on petitions 
asking the park service to reconsider its plan to catch the 
animals break them and then allow the public to adopt them for 
a fee 
its silly for the park service to think about removing them 
no matter how many times youve seem them its always a thrill 
says gay healzer of eminence a rodeo champion in barrel 
competition 
the government claims the animals are not truly wild like the 
mustangs roaming western ranges and therefore are not able to 
contend with harsh winters disease injury and food shortages 
in addition the horses create unwanted trails trample rare and 
endangered plants and occasionally raid the hay fields of farmers 
who lease federal land says tom graham chief ranger of the ozark 
national scenic riverways 
we heard from an individual that three horses were shot 
recently and left to die graham says there are occasional 
reports that humans are abusing them 
moreover the agency is legally bound to remove the horses 
because nonnative animals are not allowed to inhabit park service 
lands he says 
the government will choose this summer from bids submitted by 
individuals and businesses wishing to capture the horses the 
missouri humane society will be asked to monitor the roundup to 
ensure the animals safety graham says 
smotherman calls the governments reasoning a bunch of 
baloney 
its unlikely the horses three separate bands of about eight 
animals each led by a stallion would ever become overpopulated 
he says deer cause more damage to farm fields than the horses he 
adds 
the park service has enough room down there to pasture 400 to 
500 head smotherman says 
the horses are mostly mixed breeds including several 
appaloosas because they are inbred most of the animals wouldnt 
bring more than 400 to 500 a head at market smotherman says 
if somebody comes in here and catches them ill guarantee 
that 90 percent of them will be turned into dog food smotherman 
says a lot of them are mares 15 to 20 years old theyre not 
going to be able to break them colts theyll be able to break the 
older they get the harder it is to break them 
tom mooney of eminence remembers seeing horses running wild when 
he was a child at his familys home on blairs creek before 
congress established the ozark national scenic riverways in 1962 to 
preserve the natural beauty of the area 
those horses were there before the park service mooney 
says theyve never hurt anything i love to see them here and 
id love to see them stay here 
jim smith whose family has operated wilderness trail rides at 
eminence for 35 years questions the governments contention that 
the stray horses arent wild he said hes seen the horses swim 
across a river or flee up a steep rocky hillside at the mere sight 
of a human 
you cant catch them he says ive chased em a little 
bit myself shoot they outrun you you can run a horse to death 
and youll never get a rope on one people have tried for years 
despite public sentiment graham says the government wont budge 
from its position that the horses must go 
we have a legal obligation to do this he says 
