<TEXT>
 
days of open hand aampm suzanne vega 
 
suzanne vegas voice is a remarkable instrument though thin and 
delicate it broke down barriers and opened a new market for female 
singers vegas popularity with a folkpop sound paved the way for 
such women as sinead oconnor and tracy chapman who made some of 
the best music of the late 1980s 
while the genre has thrived vega has struggled its been three 
years since her last album and surprise hit luka she 
complained of writers block after her first two records used up a 
lifetimes accumulation of material 
so with the release of days of open hand the question is 
how good are the songs and the answer is just fair the record 
doesnt have anything approaching the beauty of luka few 
albums do and the pace flags toward the end of the 11song set 
vegas lyrics are as fascinatingly opaque as ever men in a 
war about abortion and fiftyfifty chance about suicide 
both deliver lateverse twists and theyre the most 
straightforward songs on the record words are at the heart of her 
art which vega acknowledges on big space between the pen 
and the paperweight i know theres passion in the language 
the shimmering quality of vegas best music is absent here most 
of the time possibly because her acoustic guitar is less prominent 
than previously thats unfortunate the combination of vegas 
voice and strummed guitar is one of the prettiest in pop 
her search for new sounds brings to the foreground synthesizers 
big space and strings the philip glassish fiftyfifty 
chance vegas slower songs place more emphasis on texture and 
less on rhythmic punch than in the past 
clearly vega wants her music to evolve which is healthy and 
bound to produce interesting results but days of open hand is 
a dense record not anxious to win the affection of its listeners 
that thin delicate voice is most assertive suzanne vega 
continues to make music on her own terms 
by steven wine associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
reading writing and arithmetic david geffen co the 
sundays 
 
britons harriet wheeler and david gavurin make songs about 
moments and like most moments the songs on reading writing and 
