<TEXT>
in the shops and on the streets of west 
virginias westernmost town the topic these days is more likely to 
center on oil refinery emissions lawsuits and harassment than on 
high school football 
more than 3 billion in lawsuits filed by more than 1000 
residents against ashland oil inc have caused a bitter split in 
kenova neighbor is pitted against neighbor as the issue of jobs 
vs pollution is played out in this town of 5000 
its tearing our town apart said mayor frank heck i look 
for it to start splitting churches and families apart here 
the harsh words and hard feelings are found in places usually 
concerned with the chances of ceredokenova high school winning 
another state football championship 
the residents who have filed suit contend that emissions from 
ashland oils giant catlettsburg ky refinery just across the big 
sandy river have damaged their health and their property 
the kentucky division for air quality a state organization 
found the emissions consisted of flakes of caustic lime dust a 
claylike substance used in a refinery product 
the residents said they were alarmed by dying trees on their 
property and that they suffered from skin rashes and breathing 
problems they also said the emissions have peeled the paint off 
their cars a kanawha county circuit court jury agreed in may 
awarding 10 million in damages to the first four plaintiffs 
ashland oil has appealed the verdict and the company one of 
the biggest employers in an economically troubled area has plenty 
of supporters ashland oil says it employs more than 2700 people 
in west virginia 
supporters have been flooding newspapers from ashland to 
charleston 60 miles away with letters to the editor challenging 
the verdict 
