<TEXT>
the manufacturing sector of the nations economy 
grew for the third consecutive month in june according to a survey 
of corporate purchasing executives released today 
the purchasing managers index released monthly by the national 
association of purchasing management rose slightly to 511 percent 
from 507 in may the group said from its tempe ariz 
headquarters 
a reading above 50 indicates the economy generally is expanding 
below 50 that it generally is contracting june marked the third 
straight month the index was above 50 the 11 previous months the 
index declined 
the purchasing managers index a composite figure of survey 
results on order levels prices employment and other areas 
averaged 491 percent for the first half of the year 
if the june index reading is repeated for the rest of the year 
it would be consistent with real gross national product growth of 
about 19 percent according to past experience the group said 
the manufacturing economy ended the second quarter with a 
moderate but solid increase in growth said robert j bretz 
chairman of the groups business survey committee 
the groups production index rose for the fifth consecutive 
month although at a lower rate than in may its new orders index 
also rose for the fifth straight month at virtually the same rate 
as in may 
the new export orders figure increased at a stronger rate than 
in may while imports fell for the second consecutive month 
inventories declined for the 19th consecutive month although the 
rate of decline was at the lowest since december 1989 
deliveries from suppliers were slower in june for the first time 
in 14 months reflecting the increased demand and lower inventory 
levels the group said 
prices rose in june for the second time in the last three 
months and the groups price index stood at its highest level 
since may 1989 
the purchasing managers group represents chief purchasing 
executives at more than 300 industrial companies 
</TEXT>
