publisher ralph ingersoll ii said today he 
agreed to swap the controlling stake in his us newspaper chains 
for european publishing interests after failing to make an interest 
payment on highrisk junk bonds 
ingersoll is the latest entrepreneur to run into debt 
difficulties after building an empire in the 1980s with junkbond 
financing 
the announcement followed months of attempts by ingersoll to buy 
back his companies junk bonds at steep discounts to alleviate a 
heavy debt burden 
ingersolls announcement also comes a little more than two 
months after he folded the st louis sun a new tabloid that 
ingersoll claimed would revolutionize the slumping newspaper market 
by using new technology and marketing strategies 
under the agreement ingersoll is relinquishing his stake in 
three companies that publish dozens of daily and weekly newspapers 
to the new york investment firm em warburg pincus amp co the two 
had been joint owners although ingersoll exercised voting control 
warburg pincus gains full control of ingersoll newspapers inc 
which publishes nine dailies and 53 weeklies new haven acquisition 
co publisher of the new haven register and community newspapers 
inc which has newspapers mostly in ohio and on new yorks long 
island 
in return ingersoll will gain full control of a group of 
british and irish newspapers that he had owned jointly with 
warburg pincus the newspapers have combined circulations 
exceeding 1 million and annual revenues of 178 million 
in a telephone interview ingersoll said the deal matched his 
desire to get more involved in european publishing and the desire 
of warburg pincus to expand its role in the us market 
the missed bond payment has zero to do with the trade we did 
today ingersoll said the us companies are profitable but no 
one could forsee the collapse of the junk bond market that 
torpedoed the bond issue he said 
nevertheless when asked if he would have preferred to retain 
his us holdings while expanding into europe he responded 
would i like to have them both sure 
ingersolls companies went on an expansion spree with proceeds 
from junk bonds issued by nowcollapsed drexel burnham lambert 
inc the wall street investment bank that once dominated the 
market in junkbond securities 
but the collapse of the junk market in recent months sent the 
price of community newspapers 125 million of 13 percent bonds 
plunging to as low as 40 cents on the dollar that put ingersoll in 
a bind because community newspapers was required to reset terms on 
the bonds to make them trade at 101 
no one ever imagined that the reset would become unworkable 
he said 
community newspapers said it would not make the interest payment 
due july 1 on the 13 percent bonds in addition the company said 
it would not reset the interest rate on those bonds on july 7 as 
it was supposed to do 
