<DOCNO> AP900702-0240 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations manufacturing economy grew for the 
third consecutive month in june according to an influential survey 
of corporate purchasing executives 
it indicates that the manufacturing sector is not so weak as 
to suggest that a recession is drawing near said john lonski 
chief economist for moodys investors service inc 
other economists were less optimistic pointing out that 
manufacturing accounts for only about 20 percent of the economy 
david hale chief economist at kemper financial services inc in 
chicago said the key to avoiding a recession is consumer spending 
which comprises about twothirds of the nations economic activity 
if consumers continue to be cautious or cut their spending further 
it could spell trouble he said 
the manufacturing survey is taken monthly by the national 
association of purchasing management which includes chief 
purchasing executives at more than 300 industrial companies 
the group said its purchasing managers index rose slightly in 
june to 511 percent from 507 in may a reading above 50 indicates 
the economy generally is expanding below 50 that it generally is 
contracting 
june marked the third straight month the index was above 50 the 
11 previous months the index declined 
the index a composite of survey results on order levels 
prices inventory and other areas averaged 491 percent for the 
first half of the year 
if the june index reading is repeated for the rest of the year 
it would be consistent with real gross national product growth of 
about 19 percent based on past experience the group said from 
its tempe ariz headquarters 
the manufacturing economy ended the second quarter with a 
moderate but solid increase in growth said robert j bretz 
chairman of te groups business survey committee 
hale said the strength in the index is less significant than it 
appears because much if not all of it stemmed from rising car 
production automakers which scaled back production in april 
stepped up manufacturing in may and june he said 
other economists disagreed ken goldstein of the conference 
board a new yorkbased business group said manufacturing overall 
has been picking up strength 
if anything the purchasing managers report might be 
understating the momentum in the industrial sector of the 
economy he said 
lonski said the commercial aircraft industry is the only other 
manufacturing sector aside from autos that was strong but there 
were pockets of strength in other areas such as computers and 
pharmaceuticals he said 
the june survey also included questions on credit conditions of 
the 18 percent of responding members whose companies had sought 
credit from a financial institution since april few said they 
experienced tougher lending restrictions or felt the need to issue 
commercial paper as an alternative to bank loans 
but a number of members said their smaller suppliers or 
customers had trouble obtaining credit 
among the components of the purchasing managers index 
production by the member companies rose for the fifth consecutive 
month although at a lower rate than in may 
new orders placed with the manufacturers also rose for the fifth 
straight month at virtually the same rate as in may new export 
orders increased at a stronger rate than in may 
imports by the manufacturers fell for the second consecutive 
month 
deliveries from suppliers were slower in june for the first time 
in 14 months reflecting increased demand for raw materials and 
lower inventory levels maintained by these suppliers the group 
said 
prices of raw materials bought by the manufacturers rose in june 
for the second time in the last three months and the groups price 
index stood at its highest level since may 1989 
the level of inventories maintained by the manufacturers 
declined for the 19th consecutive month although the rate of 
decline was the lowest since december 1989 
lonski said the inventory decline could be good news if the 
nation enters a recession with little backlog manufacturing would 
have to pick up quickly once the economy resumes strength by 
contrast in the 1982 recession manufacturers particularly 
carmakers were caught with huge inventories that had to be sold 
before they could resume production 
</TEXT>
