<TEXT>
venezuela expects to enter the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade in september after an international 
working group approved its membership last week venezuelas chief 
negotiator announced monday 
acceptance of venezuela into the 96nation trade group had been 
delayed by objections from the united states and the european 
economic community which complained about high tariffs and 
subsidies granted to domestic business 
but chief negotiator miguel rodriguez mendoza said a compromise 
was struck venezuela agreed to limit tariffs reduce a 5 percent 
valueadded tax the government imposes on imports and soften a law 
that encourages public companies to buy venezuelan rodriguez 
mendoza said 
he said gatt members would vote on venezuelas membership july 
11 twothirds of gatt nations or 64 countries must approve and 
rodriguez mendoza said approval was all but assured 
venezuela applied to enter the gatt last year after tight 
finances forced the country to move from a statecontrolled to a 
free market economy 
venezuela derives 90 percent of its export income from oil but 
the government wants to diversify its manufacturing 
