<TEXT>
forecasts for sizzling temperatures in the midwest sparked sharp 
gains monday in soybean and pork futures prices amid speculation 
that hot weather will scorch the bean crop and slow the movement of 
hogs to market 
on other commodity markets most grain futures advanced cattle 
futures were mixed oil futures mostly were lower and precious 
metals rose modestly 
on the chicago board of trade soybean futures settled 5 cents 
to 23 cents higher with the contract for delivery in july up 22 
cents at 646 a bushel wheat futures finished cent to 2 cents 
higher with july at 326 a bushel corn was 3 cents lower to 2 
cents higher with july at 296 a bushel oats were 3 cents to 3 
cents higher with july at 139 a bushel 
in pork futures trading on the chicago mercantile exchange hogs 
finished 87 cent to 14 cents higher with july at 6127 cents a 
pound frozen pork bellies were 95 cent to the permitted daily 
limit of 2 cents higher with july at 5967 cents a pound live 
cattle were 27 cent lower to 55 cent higher with august at 7280 
cents a pound feeder cattle were 15 cent to 57 cent lower with 
august at 8345 cents a pound 
analysts attributed the bullish tone in pork and beans largely 
to forecasts that 100plusdegree temperatures would move into the 
nations agricultural midsection from the southwest 
temperatures above 100 degrees were reported in southeastern 
nebraska monday afternoon the heatbearing highpressure front 
was expected to continue moving east over the next few days 
hot dry weather would be especially stressful to crops in the 
western and southern reaches of the corn belt where conditions 
already are dry analysts said 
hot weather also could slow marketings of hogs which tend to 
lose weight more quickly as temperatures rise said thomas morgan 
president of sterling research inc an analytical service in 
arlington heights ill 
of course this is only a temporary thing he said this 
heat is supposed to be gone by wednesday or thursday 
but a number of influential weather forecasters on monday issued 
longerterm predictions for warmer and drierthannormal weather 
in parts of the midwest 
freesenotis weather inc of des moines iowa was one of 
several private meteorological firms predicting abovenormal 
temperatures and belownormal rainfall in july for areas including 
western iowa nebraska southern illinois and the mississippi delta 
region 
the pattern were predicting resembles that of 1980 when 
southern corn belt and delta crops were severely hurt said 
charles notis a partner in the private forecasting firm 
the national weather service which last week projected normal 
july temperatures and precipitation issued a sixto10day outlook 
late monday predicting abovenormal temperatures and normal to 
belownormal rainfall in the midwest for july 812 
the agriculture department meanwhile released its weekly 
cropprogress report it indicated soybean planting was 95 percent 
complete as of sunday with 54 percent of the crop in good to 
excellent condition compared with 55 percent a week earlier 
the usda rated the corn crop 65 percent good to excellent 
compared with 64 percent a week earlier 
the usda also reported the winter wheat harvest was 50 percent 
complete as of sunday and rated 77 percent of the spring wheat crop 
good to excellent unchanged from a week earlier 
