<TEXT>
an oil workers union on monday accepted a 
government order to end a oneday strike on norways offshore 
platforms but said its members refused to return to work 
we have lost control of our members said union official 
oddleiv tonnessen in a telephone interview production in the 
norwegian north sea is still completely at a standstill 
at some offshore oil platforms wildcat strikers barricaded 
helicopter landing pads to keep new crews from landing he said 
but helicopter pilots told reporters they had few problems while 
flying hundreds of workers back to their platforms 
norways north sea fields produced 163 million barrels of oil 
per day and 18 billion cubic meters of natural gas a month in 
april news reports said lost production costs norway up to 200 
million kroner or 31 million a day 
the legal strike began at midnight saturday after lastminute 
bargaining failed to produce agreement union members walked out in 
a dispute with the norwegian confederation of business and industry 
over wages and job protection against automation 
the union said the employers offer of a 25percent pay raise 
was less than half its demand the employers group said offshore 
oil workers already average 313000 kroner or 49000 a year 85 
percent above the average onshore industrial wage 
the government ordered 4000 strikers back to work monday after 
the strike shut down the countrys offshore oil platforms sunday 
municipalities minister johan j jakobsen said compulsory 
arbitration was invoked to protect the national economy he said 
onequarter of norways national income comes from oil 
the norwegian federation of oil workers union central committee 
accepted the government backtowork order and told its members to 
return to work 
but tonnessen said workers on many platforms defied the order by 
continuing the strike illegally ntb quoted strikers as saying they 
will stay off the job until their demands are met 
there have been some widespread problems said boerge 
bekkeheien of the oil industry association after meeting with the 
unionwe hope things will return to normal tuesday 
norways last major offshore strike lasted 20 days in 1986 and 
ended with a compulsory arbitration order 
